# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sample-and-hold
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] In electromagnetics and antenna theory, the **aperture** of an antenna is defined as "A surface, near or on an antenna, on which it is convenient to make assumptions regarding the field values for the purpose of computing fields at external points.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] The incoming radiation is assumed to have the same polarization as the antenna.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] The effective area of an antenna or aperture is based upon a *receiving* antenna.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] However, due to reciprocity, an antenna's directivity in receiving and transmitting are identical, so the power transmitted by an antenna in different directions (the radiation pattern) is also proportional to the effective area $A_{e}$ .
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] When no direction is specified, $A_{e}$ is understood to refer to its maximal value.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] Most antenna designs are not defined by a physical area but consist of wires or thin rods; then the effective aperture bears no clear relation to the size or area of the antenna.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] The longer the effective length, the greater is the voltage appearing at its terminals.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] However, the actual power implied by that voltage depends on the antenna's feedpoint impedance, so this cannot be directly related to antenna gain, which *is* a measure of received power (but does not directly specify voltage or current).
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] For instance, a half-wave dipole has a much longer effective length than a short dipole.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] However the effective area of the short dipole is almost as great as it is for the half-wave antenna, since (ideally), given an ideal impedance-matching network, it can receive almost as much power from that wave.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] Note that for a given antenna feedpoint impedance, an antenna's gain or $A_{\text{eff}}$ increases according to the *square* of $l_{\text{eff}}$ , so that the effective length for an antenna relative to different wave directions follows the *square root* of the gain in those directions.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] But since changing the physical size of an antenna inevitably changes the impedance (often by a great factor), the effective length is not by itself a useful figure of merit for describing an antenna's peak directivity and is more of theoretical importance.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] In practice, the effective length of a particular antenna is often combined with its impedance and loss to become the realized effective length.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] In general, the aperture of an antenna cannot be directly inferred from its physical size.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] That power removed from the plane wave can be actually received by the antenna (converted into electrical power), reflected or otherwise scattered, or absorbed (converted to heat).
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] In this case the *effective aperture* $A_{e}$ is always less than (or equal to) the area of the antenna's physical aperture $A_{\text{phys}}$ , as it accounts only for the portion of that wave actually received as electrical power.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] The **aperture efficiency** is a dimensionless parameter between 0 and 1 that measures how close the antenna comes to using all the radio wave power intersecting its physical aperture.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] If the aperture efficiency were 100%, then all the wave's power falling on its physical aperture would be converted to electrical power delivered to the load attached to its output terminals, so these two areas would be equal: $A_{\text{e}}=A_{\text{phys}}$ .
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] But due to nonuniform illumination by a parabolic dish's feed, as well as other scattering or loss mechanisms, this is not achieved in practice.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] Since a parabolic antenna's cost and wind load increase with the *physical* aperture size, there may be a strong motivation to reduce these (while achieving a specified antenna gain) by maximizing the aperture efficiency.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] Aperture efficiencies of typical aperture antennas vary from 0.35 to well over 0.70.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] Note that when one simply speaks of an antenna's "efficiency", what is most often meant is the *radiation efficiency*, a measure which applies to all antennas (not just aperture antennas) and accounts only for the gain reduction due to losses.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] Outside of aperture antennas, most antennas consist of thin wires or rods with a small physical cross-sectional area (generally much smaller than $A_{\text{e}}$ ) for which "aperture efficiency" is not even defined.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] The *directivity* of an antenna, its ability to direct radio waves preferentially in one direction or receive preferentially from a given direction, is expressed by a parameter G called *antenna gain*.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] This is most commonly defined as the ratio of the power $P_{\text{o}}$ received by that antenna from waves in a given direction to the power $P_{\text{iso}}$ that would be received by an ideal isotropic antenna, that is, a hypothetical antenna that receives power equally well from all directions.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] where $\lambda$ is the wavelength of the radio waves.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] So antennas with large effective apertures are considered high-gain antennas (or *beam antennas*), which have relatively small angular beam widths.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] As receiving antennas, they are much more sensitive to radio waves coming from a preferred direction compared to waves coming from other directions (which would be considered interference).
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] As transmitting antennas, most of their power is radiated in a particular direction at the expense of other directions.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] Although antenna gain and effective aperture are functions of direction, when no direction is specified, these are understood to refer to their maximal values, that is, in the direction(s) of the antenna's intended use (also referred to as the antenna's main lobe or boresight).
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] The fraction of the power delivered to a transmitting antenna that is received by a receiving antenna is proportional to the product of the apertures of both the antennas and inversely proportional to the squared values of the distance between the antennas and the wavelength.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] is the wavelength of the radio frequency.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] The aperture of an isotropic antenna, the basis of the definition of gain above, can be derived on the basis of consistency with thermodynamics.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] Suppose that an ideal isotropic antenna *A* with a driving-point impedance of *R* sits within a closed system CA in thermodynamic equilibrium at temperature *T*.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] We connect the antenna terminals to a resistor also of resistance *R* inside a second closed system CR, also at temperature *T*.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] In between may be inserted an arbitrary lossless electronic filter *Fν* passing only some frequency components.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] Each cavity is in thermal equilibrium and thus filled with black-body radiation due to temperature *T*.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] The mean-squared voltage ${\overline {v_{n}^{2}}}={\text{v}}_{\text{rms}}^{2}$ can be found by integrating the above equation for the spectral density of mean-squared noise voltage over frequencies passed by the filter *Fν*.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] This power due to Johnson noise from the resistor is received by the antenna, which radiates it into the closed system CA.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] using the notation $\eta (f)$ defined above.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] However, that radiation is unpolarized, whereas the antenna is only sensitive to one polarization, reducing it by a factor of 2.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] Since we have assumed an isotropic radiator, *A*eff is independent of angle, so the integration over solid angles is trivial, introducing a factor of 4π.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] And again we can take the simple case of a narrowband electronic filter function *Fν* which only passes power of bandwidth *B*1 around frequency *f*1.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] where $\lambda _{1}=c/f_{1}$ is the free-space wavelength corresponding to the frequency *f*1.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] Since each system is in thermodynamic equilibrium at the same temperature, we expect no net transfer of power between the cavities.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] Otherwise one cavity would heat up and the other would cool down in violation of the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] We thus find that for a hypothetical isotropic antenna, thermodynamics demands that the effective cross-section of the receiving antenna to have an area of λ2/4π.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] This result could be further generalized if we allow the integral over frequency to be more general.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] Then we find that *A*eff for the same antenna must vary with frequency according to that same formula, using λ = *c*/*f*.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] Moreover, the integral over solid angle can be generalized for an antenna that is *not* isotropic (that is, any real antenna).
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] Although the above is sufficient proof, we can note that the condition of the antenna's impedance being *R*, the same as the resistor, can also be relaxed.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] In principle, any antenna impedance (that isn't totally reactive) can be impedance-matched to the resistor *R* by inserting a suitable (lossless) matching network.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] Since that network is lossless, the powers *P*A and *P*R will still flow in opposite directions, even though the voltage and currents seen at the antenna and resistor's terminals will differ.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] The spectral density of the power flow in either direction will still be given by $k_{\text{B}}T\,\eta (f)$ , and in fact this is the very thermal-noise power spectral density associated with one electromagnetic mode, be it in free-space or transmitted electrically.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] Since there is only a single connection to the resistor, the resistor itself represents a single mode.
[src:sample-and-hold/aperture-antenna] And an antenna, also having a single electrical connection, couples to one mode of the electromagnetic field according to its average effective cross-section of $\lambda _{1}^{2}/(4\pi )$ .
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] In electronics and telecommunications, **jitter** is the deviation from true periodicity of a presumably periodic signal, often in relation to a reference clock signal.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] In clock recovery applications it is called **timing jitter**.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Jitter is a significant, and usually undesired, factor in the design of almost all communications links.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Jitter can be quantified in the same terms as all time-varying signals, e.g., root mean square (RMS), or peak-to-peak displacement.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Also, like other time-varying signals, jitter can be expressed in terms of spectral density.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Jitter may be caused by electromagnetic interference and crosstalk with carriers of other signals.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Jitter can cause a display monitor to flicker, affect the performance of processors in personal computers, introduce clicks or other undesired effects in audio signals, and cause loss of transmitted data between network devices.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] The amount of tolerable jitter depends on the affected application.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] in the position of a clock's edge from where it would ideally be.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Maximum error committed by a clock under test in measuring a time interval for a given period of time.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] The difference between any one clock period and the ideal or average clock period.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Hence, synchronous circuitry benefits from minimizing period jitter, so that the shortest clock period approaches the average clock period.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] The difference in duration of any two adjacent clock periods.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] In telecommunications, the unit used for the above types of jitter is usually the unit interval (UI) which quantifies the jitter in terms of a fraction of the transmission unit period.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] This unit is useful because it scales with clock frequency and thus allows relatively slow interconnects such as T1 to be compared to higher-speed internet backbone links such as OC-192.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Absolute units such as *picoseconds* are more common in microprocessor applications.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Units of *degrees* and *radians* are also used.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] If jitter has a Gaussian distribution, it is usually quantified using the standard deviation of this distribution.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] This translates to an RMS measurement for a zero-mean distribution.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Often, jitter distribution is significantly non-Gaussian.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] This can occur if the jitter is caused by external sources such as power supply noise.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] In these cases, *peak-to-peak* measurements may be more useful.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Many efforts have been made to meaningfully quantify distributions that are neither Gaussian nor have a meaningful peak level.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] All have shortcomings but most tend to be good enough for the purposes of engineering work.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] In computer networking, *jitter* can refer to packet delay variation, the variation (statistical dispersion) in the delay of the packets.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] One of the main differences between random and deterministic jitter is that deterministic jitter is bounded and random jitter is unbounded.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Random jitter, also called Gaussian jitter, is unpredictable electronic timing noise.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Random jitter typically follows a normal distribution due to being caused by thermal noise in an electrical circuit.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] in which the value of *n* is based on the BER required of the link.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] A common BER used in communication standards such as Ethernet is 10−12.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] In analog-to-digital and digital-to-analog conversion of signals, the sampling is normally assumed to be periodic with a fixed period—the time between every two samples is the same.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] If there is jitter present on the clock signal to the analog-to-digital converter or a digital-to-analog converter, the time between samples varies and instantaneous signal error arises.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] The error is proportional to the slew rate of the desired signal and the absolute value of the clock error.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] The effect of jitter on the signal depends on the nature of the jitter.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Random jitter tends to add broadband noise while deterministic jitter tends to add errant spectral components, *birdys*.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] In some conditions, less than a nanosecond of jitter can reduce the effective bit resolution of a converter with a Nyquist frequency of 22 kHz to 14 bits.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Sampling jitter is an important consideration in high-frequency signal conversion, or where the clock signal is especially prone to interference.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] In digital antenna arrays ADC and DAC jitters are the important factors determining the direction of arrival estimation accuracy and the depth of jammers suppression.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] In the context of computer networks, packet jitter or packet delay variation (PDV) is the variation in latency as measured in the variability over time of the end-to-end delay across a network.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] A network with constant delay has no packet jitter.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Packet jitter is expressed as an average of the deviation from the network mean delay.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] PDV is an important quality of service factor in assessment of network performance.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Transmitting a burst of traffic at a high rate followed by an interval or period of lower or zero rate transmission may also be seen as a form of jitter, as it represents a deviation from the average transmission rate.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] However, unlike the jitter caused by variation in latency, transmitting in bursts may be seen as a desirable feature, e.g. in variable bitrate transmissions.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Video or image jitter occurs when the horizontal lines of video image frames are randomly displaced due to the corruption of synchronization signals or electromagnetic interference during video transmission.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] A model-based dejittering study has been carried out under the framework of digital image and video restoration.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Jitter in serial bus architectures is measured by means of eye patterns.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] There are standards for jitter measurement in serial bus architectures.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] The standards cover jitter tolerance, jitter transfer function and jitter generation, with the required values for these attributes varying among different applications.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Where applicable, compliant systems are required to conform to these standards.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Testing for jitter and its measurement is of growing importance to electronics engineers because of increased clock frequencies in digital electronic circuitry to achieve higher device performance.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Higher clock frequencies have commensurately smaller eye openings and thus impose tighter tolerances on jitter.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] For example, modern computer motherboards have serial bus architectures with eye openings of 160 picoseconds or less.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] This is extremely small compared to parallel bus architectures with equivalent performance, which may have eye openings on the order of 1000 picoseconds.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Jitter is measured and evaluated in various ways depending on the type of circuit under test.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] In all cases, the goal of jitter measurement is to verify that the jitter will not disrupt normal operation of the circuit.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Testing of device performance for jitter tolerance may involve injection of jitter into electronic components with specialized test equipment.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] A less direct approach—in which analog waveforms are digitized and the resulting data stream analyzed—is employed when measuring pixel jitter in frame grabbers.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Anti-jitter circuits (AJCs) are a class of electronic circuits designed to reduce the level of jitter in a clock signal.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] AJCs operate by re-timing the output pulses so they align more closely to an idealized clock.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] They are widely used in clock and data recovery circuits in digital communications, as well as for data sampling systems such as the analog-to-digital converter and digital-to-analog converter.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Examples of anti-jitter circuits include phase-locked loop and delay-locked loop.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Jitter buffers or de-jitter buffers are buffers used to counter jitter introduced by queuing in packet-switched networks to ensure continuous playout of an audio or video media stream transmitted over the network.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] The maximum jitter that can be countered by a de-jitter buffer is equal to the buffering delay introduced before starting the play-out of the media stream.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] In the context of packet-switched networks, the term *packet delay variation* is often preferred over *jitter*.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Some systems use sophisticated delay-optimal de-jitter buffers that are capable of adapting the buffering delay to changing network characteristics.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] The adaptation logic is based on the jitter estimates computed from the arrival characteristics of the media packets.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Adjustments associated with adaptive de-jittering involve introducing discontinuities in the media play-out, which may be noticeable to the listener or viewer.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] Adaptive de-jittering is usually carried out for audio play-outs that include voice activity detection, which allows the lengths of the silence periods to be adjusted, thus minimizing the perceptual impact of the adaptation.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] A dejitterizer is a device that reduces jitter in a digital signal.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] A dejitterizer usually consists of an elastic buffer in which the signal is temporarily stored and then retransmitted at a rate based on the average rate of the incoming signal.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] A dejitterizer may not be effective in removing low-frequency jitter (wander).
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] A filter can be designed to minimize the effect of sampling jitter.
[src:sample-and-hold/jitter] A jitter signal can be decomposed into intrinsic mode functions (IMFs), which can be further applied for filtering or dejittering.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] In electronics, a **sample and hold** (also known as sample and follow) circuit is an analog device that samples (captures, takes) the voltage of a continuously varying analog signal and holds (locks, freezes) its value at a constant level for a specified minimum period of time.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] Sample and hold circuits and related peak detectors are the elementary analog memory devices.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] They are typically used in analog-to-digital converters to eliminate variations in input signal that can corrupt the conversion process.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] They are also used in electronic music, for instance to impart a random quality to successively-played notes.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] A typical sample and hold circuit stores electric charge in a capacitor and contains at least one switching device such as a FET (field effect transistor) switch and normally one operational amplifier.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] To sample the input signal, the switch connects the capacitor to the output of a buffer amplifier.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] The buffer amplifier charges or discharges the capacitor so that the voltage across the capacitor is practically equal, or proportional to, input voltage.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] In hold mode, the switch disconnects the capacitor from the buffer.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] The capacitor is invariably discharged by its own leakage currents and useful load currents, which makes the circuit inherently volatile, but the loss of voltage (*voltage drop*) within a specified hold time remains within an acceptable error margin for all but the most demanding applications.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] Sample and hold circuits are used in linear systems.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] In some kinds of analog-to-digital converters (ADCs), the input is compared to a voltage generated internally from a digital-to-analog converter (DAC).
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] The circuit tries a series of values and stops converting once the voltages are equal, within some defined error margin.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] If the input value was permitted to change during this comparison process, the resulting conversion would be inaccurate and possibly unrelated to the true input value.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] Such successive approximation converters will often incorporate internal sample and hold circuitry.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] In addition, sample and hold circuits are often used when multiple samples need to be measured at the same time.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] Each value is sampled and held, using a common sample clock.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] In order to maintain the level during a scanning cycle (frame period), an additional electric capacitor is attached in parallel to each LC pixel to better hold the voltage.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] A thin-film FET switch is addressed to select a particular LC pixel and charge the picture information for it.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] In contrast to an S/H in general electronics, there is no output operational amplifier and no electrical signal AO.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] Instead, the charge on the hold capacitors controls the deformation of the LC molecules and thereby the optical effect as its output.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] The invention of this concept and its implementation in thin-film technology have been honored with the IEEE Jun-ichi Nishizawa Medal.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] During a scanning cycle, the picture doesn't follow the input signal.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] This does not allow the eye to refresh and can lead to blurring during motion sequences, also the transition is visible between frames because the backlight is constantly illuminated, adding to display motion blur.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] Sample and hold circuits are also frequently found on synthesizers, either as a discrete module or as an integral component.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] They are used to take periodic samples of an incoming signal, typically as a source of modulation for other components of the synthesizer.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] When a sample and hold circuit is plugged into a white noise generator the result is a sequence of random values, which—depending on the amplitude of modulation—can be used to provide subtle variations in a signal or wildly varying random tones.
[src:sample-and-hold/sample-and-hold] To keep the input voltage as stable as possible, it is essential that the capacitor have very low leakage, and that it not be loaded to any significant degree which calls for a very high input impedance.
[src:sample-and-hold/zero-order-hold] The **zero-order hold** (**ZOH**) is a mathematical model of the practical signal reconstruction done by a conventional digital-to-analog converter (DAC).
[src:sample-and-hold/zero-order-hold] That is, it describes the effect of converting a discrete-time signal to a continuous-time signal by holding each sample value for one sample interval.
[src:sample-and-hold/zero-order-hold] It has several applications in electrical communication.
[src:sample-and-hold/zero-order-hold] The function $\mathrm {rect} \left({\frac {t-T/2}{T}}\right)$ is depicted in Figure 1, and $x_{\mathrm {ZOH} }(t)$ is the piecewise-constant signal depicted in Figure 2.
[src:sample-and-hold/zero-order-hold] The equation above for the output of the ZOH can also be modeled as the output of a linear time-invariant filter with impulse response equal to a rect function, and with input being a sequence of dirac impulses scaled to the sample values.
[src:sample-and-hold/zero-order-hold] The filter can then be analyzed in the frequency domain, for comparison with other reconstruction methods such as the Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula suggested by the Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem, or such as the first-order hold or linear interpolation between sample values.
[src:sample-and-hold/zero-order-hold] In this method, a sequence of Dirac impulses, *x*s(*t*), representing the discrete samples, *x*[*n*], is low-pass filtered to recover a continuous-time signal, *x*(*t*).
[src:sample-and-hold/zero-order-hold] The scaling by T , which arises naturally by time-scaling the delta function, has the result that the mean value of *xs*(*t*) is equal to the mean value of the samples, so that the lowpass filter needed will have a DC gain of 1.
[src:sample-and-hold/zero-order-hold] Some authors use this scaling, while many others omit the time-scaling and the *T*, resulting in a low-pass filter model with a DC gain of *T*, and hence dependent on the units of measurement of time.
[src:sample-and-hold/zero-order-hold] The effective frequency response is the continuous Fourier transform of the impulse response.
[src:sample-and-hold/zero-order-hold] This drop is a consequence of the *hold* property of a conventional DAC, and is *not* due to the sample and hold that might precede a conventional analog-to-digital converter (ADC).
